All cats were examined for FeLV antigen, and antibodies to FHV, FCV, FPV, FCoV, FeSFV and FIV. They were all negative for FeLV p27 antigen by ELISA, and for antibodies to FHV (<1:20), FCV (<1:20), FPV (<1:25), FCoV (<1:25) and FeSFV (<1:25). Cats of group 1 from which FIV had been re-isolated numerous times (Hofmann-Lehmann et al., 1997), were positive for antibodies to TM measured by ELISA, while cats of group 2 were ELISA-negative (Table 1
). Cats of group 1 had significantly lower absolute CD4+ lymphocyte counts (p=0.0025, Fig. 1
), and significant lower CD4+:CD8+ ratio (p=0.0043, data not shown) than cats of group 2.
